data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with MSTest's modern assertion APIs — each gives a clear failure message instead of just "Assert.IsTrue failed":

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in "all match" assert; IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);  // or see below
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your original | Modern equivalent | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs generic "was false" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Failure says "value was null" |

If the admin check is really "exactly one admin exists," use `ContainsSingle` on a filtered list:

```csharp
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
// Returns the element — you can assert further on it
Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role);
```

> **Note:** `Assert.IsNotEmpty`, `Assert.HasCount`, and `Assert.ContainsSingle` require **MSTest 3.8+**. The `Assert.Contains` overload for collections is also 3.8+.
